%p It’s obvious you should “eat less and exercise more” if you are physically depressed and overweight. But eat less of <em>what</em> and do more of what <em>kind</em> of exercise?

%p It’s also obvious you should “spend less and earn more” if you are financially manic and in debt. But earn more of <em>what</em> and do less of what <em>kind</em> of spending?

%p But mental and affective imbalances are not even <em>measurable</em> and there is no obvious advice as to what you should do more or less of. Except to take sedatives if you’re manic and stimulants if you’re depressed. Which is less than helpful if you are both at the same time or cycle rapidly between the two.

%p BipolarType offers specific advice in all four realms. Not only what exactly you should do, but when to do it.


%h2 Balancing and Displacing

%p Balancing behaviors are those that reverse an imbalance: if you have gotten too much energy, the balancing behavior is #{Phase.UE.name}.

%p Displacing behaviors are those that prevent an imbalance: if you expect to get too much energy, the displacing behavior is #{Phase.GS.name}.

%p In other words, if you have gained too much fat, balancing behaviors help reverse the gain into a loss and displacing behaviors help prevent you from gaining it back again.

